4.2) I am sure (?) the winning project will publish all this but what about other participants? 

Is it really acceptable to subject a group of autistic folks to this ‚Äúexperiment‚Äù and ambiguity?

Text:
4.1) Research ethics and format: 

-Where and how will the ‚Äúparticipants‚Äù collect data from? 
-What is the methodology they will incorporate? 
-Who will they consult? 
-What sort of timeline are they following?
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
3) Ableist: 

The whole ‚Äúendevour to research prevention of autism‚Äù is ableist. 

Autism is not a disease you can cure or prevent, or a game that you can predict outcome. 
We are not talking about rolling a dice and calculating probability here. We are talking about a real person
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
2) Benefit: 

Who is this project aiming to benefit? Because if it is autistic folk ‚Äì we've repeatedly mentioned how we do not want to know how to prevent our existence. 
If you have funds, help in creating accommodations for us. Hire autistic folks to understand lived experience
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
1) Eugenics: 

Time and again autistic community has highlighted how ‚Äúprevention of autism‚Äù does not help us in anyway. It is basically a polite way to say ‚Äì we do not like this trait so we want to get rid of it, and get rid of people like you.

Text:
Honestly, in the context that I come from, I am lucky I had a late assessment (unfortunately!)

Early assessment is helpful, but not always. 

Sometimes it causes more hindrance. 

Unfortunately since most narratives are first world based, this nuance is often lost.

Text:
20. Trans people were taking hormones that killed them, underwent risky surgery. 

Now, it is no longer the case. 

While life is not perfect right now, it has improved a lot.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
19. The support group helped people make informed decision. 

They started working with families and child who wanted to transition.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
18. I came out in 1992. Back then there was very little information and trans people were not in contact with each other. They were working for their rights. 

The support groups that came up provided accurate information and ensured people understood the journey - ups and downs.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
17. About @TENI_Tweets:  
TENI was formed in Cork as a result of report by Equality Commission on services for "transsexual" people. 

It was a voluntary org. It started as professional org in 2010. We have tried to work with community, service provider
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
16. Only in 2000s, we had services in Ireland.

First psychiarty services was in 1992 when it was treated as disorder.

Endochrine services came much later. 

We were 20-30 years beind, and even now we are 10-20 years behind.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
15. In 1983 I saw BBC documentary for the first time. It was also dificult to get funding to avail services. 

Only in late 80s, I got more information. Then things opened up more - esp. in UK, Spain.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
14. But it keeps coming back, and bigger. 

I realised I needed to address it. 

Working in Dublin at 17 opened opportunities. Travelling to other countries helped too.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
13. I had a very supportive family. When I was 5, 11 and 17 - when I didnt have the language, when I tried to talk about my gender, I realised that transition was not possible back then (70s). 

There were no books on transgender in library.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
12. Streets are unsafe for transwoman too. 

I have the privilege of good job and car which keeps me save. 

Before transition, the fact that I was hiding constantly put me in danger.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
11. Sometimes we have to mask our presence before transition to keep ourself save - eg transwoman acting more masculine. 

Even 17-18 years after transition, we will still have to be mindful of how we navigate different spaces.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text: 10. We are being mindful of how we accommodate and respond to people of colour, disabled people.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
9. Before transition, patriarchy was very obvious to me. I was constantly trying to change from within. 

After transition, the industry I am in is very patriarchal. I am trying to change from within - call out things that have become second nature and they dont realise
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
8. Not everybody gets the language right. It is a learning process. If it is deliberate, it is different. But generally language is learned and it is new in this situation. 

We give space to learn about each other.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text: 7. I work in diverse areas which allows me to be in the room. It gives me the chance to push conversations we need to have and represent marginalised voices in business world.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text: 6. Women's council is working with community and groups to enhance women's life.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
5. I worked within construction industry (a male dominated industry for years but working hard to change). 

There will be increase in jobs in next 3 years which they will not be able to fill if they dont make it available and appropriate for women.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
4. Women have always been at home. Generally they are in lower paid jobs, underpaid, and not get adequate opportunities. 

 I acknowledge the privilege I had because of my background. 

And women's council is helping them bridge the gap - education, employment.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
3. Some of us have privilege that others dont have. It is important to give platform to all.

So it is important to include voices in the margin
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
2. In bringing voices from edges, there is an intersectional crossover of issues: migrant, disabled, LGBT. 

Issues such as - housing, single parents, education, public child care - effect all of us.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
1. @nwci have worked hard to be more inclusive. This was driven by women's group: migrant, transwomen. 

The motion to include and support transwoman was passed unanimously.

It is critical that we inclusive of all minority group.

6. The test: Process
- stand in line leading to the area with counters
- that bright yellow box is help desk, not the counter
- at the counter, they'll scan the QR code
- they will give a few stickers 
- stand in line for test
- give sample 
- they will stamp your boarding pass

Text:
She repeatedly told me how happy she was that V and I were so similar and V would potentially grow up to be like me.

Do you know how rare it is for a parent to tell a ND person "I want my child to be like you"? 

Everyone wants the opposite of us.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text: I would often DM her about my Pinguic moments and we would laugh about how similar I am to lil V.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:
My initial interaction with her, like most of us, was when I was in distress, and she came in with her Surekha hugs. 

When I found out I am autistic, and told her, she did not feel sorry for me. 

She celebrated each person for who they are.
Name: Priyangee ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ‡¶ô‡ßç‡¶ó‡ßÄ

Text:

She is my ally, advocate, mentor, friend, and sister. 

I have never told her any of this. 

I wish I did.
